1. Introduction¶

Medical appointment no-shows affect the delivery, cost of care and resource planning for medical professionals globally. In this notebook, will attempt to gather insights into the data surrounding no-shows for medical appointments and explore the question: which factors are important to take note of when trying to predict a no-show? To do this, we will be exploring approximately 110,000 medical appointments and its 14 associated variables from Brazil, put together by Joni Hoppen and Aquarela Advanced Analytics, which can be found here. The variables provided in the dataset are as follows:

  • PatientId: Identification of a patient
  • AppointmentID: Identification of each appointment
  • Gender: Male or Female
  • ScheduledDay: The day the appointment was was made
  • AppointmentDay: The actual appointment day
  • Age: patient age
  • Neighbourhood: Neighbourhood where of the appointment
  • Scholarship: True or False; refers to a patient’s enrolment in the Brazilian Government healthcare programme; Bolsa Família
  • Hipertension: True or False
  • Diabetes: True or False
  • Alcoholism: True or False
  • Handcap: True or False
  • SMS_received: True or False, if one or more messages has been sent to the patient
  • No-show: True or False

With the data available, through exploring the no-show rates of values within each variable, this notebook will attempt to gain insight into the question:

Which variables might be important to take note of when trying to predict a no-show?¶

With that, let’s begin by importing some libraries to help us explore the data as well as importing the data which we will be exploring.

As seen above, both ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay have been converted to the datetime64 format. With this, there are a few things we can do:

  • Calculate the number of days between scheduling and the actual appointment, which we will store in a new column waiting_days
  • Renaming AppointmentDay to AppointmentDate, to accurately reflect the data stored
  • Then extracting the day of the week from AppointmentDate, into its own column AppointmentDay

In this section, we will explore the relationships between each variable individually and if patients show up for their appointments, to attempt to shed insight on which factors should we take note of when trying to predict medical appointment no-shows.

Which variables might be important to take note of when trying to predict a no-show?¶

4.1. Gender¶

In [24]:
# Plotting both male and female shows and no-shows
sns.set_theme(style="darkgrid")

ax = sns.countplot(x=df['gender'], hue=df['no_show'])

ax.set_title("Show/NoShow between genders")
plt.ylabel('Number of Patients')
plt.xlabel('Gender')
ax.set_xticklabels(['Female', 'Male']);

From the above, we can see that the ratio of no-shows between males and females appears to be even, with around 58,000 females showing up for their appointment and 14,000 who do not. For males, around 31,000 showed up for their appointment against the approximate 8,000 that did not show up.

It is also clear that the number of female’s patients have more appointments than the male patients. This may suggest that although gender may be an important factor in predicting appointments. However, as the ratio of no-shows between the genders appear to be similar, it may not be as important in predicting no-shows.

4.2. Age¶

First, let’s take a look at distribution of shows and no-shows across age.

In [25]:
# Plotting Show/No-show across Age
plt.figure(figsize=(20,4))
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

ax = sns.countplot(x=df['age'], hue=df['no_show'])

plt.ylabel('Number of Patients')
plt.xlabel('Age')
ax.set_title('Show/No-show by Age');

From the above, we can see that the ratio of patients who show up against those who do not seem fairly consistent across the ages and that the patients under the age of 1 also have the largest number of appointments of any age.

To get a more accurate look at the ratio of shows to no-shows, we could look into the percentage of patients who showed up for their appointments by age.

4.2.1 Age by Percentage¶

In [26]:
# Percentage of patients that dont show up for their appointments by age
no_show_pecentage_age = no_show.groupby('age').size()/df.groupby('age').size()

# Plotting the Percentage of patients show up by age 
plt.figure(figsize=(20,4))
ax = sns.barplot(x=no_show_pecentage_age.index, y=no_show_pecentage_age)

# Plotting average show up line
plt.axhline(no_show_percentage, ls='--')

plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylabel('Percent of Patient No-shows')
plt.xlabel('Age')
ax.set_title('Percent of Patients No-shows Up by Age');

From the above graph we can see that:

  • On average around 20% of patients do not show up for their appointments
  • The ages 11 - 45 having a slightly higher percentage of not showing up than the average
  • The patients over the age of 45 generally do not show up slightly less than the average
  • The ages 99 - 115 present some unusual data, with either 0% or 100% rates.
    • This age groups are likely outliers in the data and may not be reliable due to the limited number of responses

Thus, due to the varying no-show percentages across ages, it appears that age may be a useful variable when trying to predict if a patient might not show for an appointment.

Although the patients without scholarships have a no-show percentage very close to the average, the patients with scholarships seem to have a average no-show of 28% which is substansitally higher than the average. This may indicate that scholarship may be a useful factor in predicting no-shows.

5. Conclusions¶

This analysis had the purpose of investigating the dataset, of over 100,000 appointments, to explore which variables may be more important when trying to predict if a patient would not show up for their scheduled appointment. The dataset was wrangled, cleaned and an exploratory data analysis exploring the no-show rates of values within each variable. This notebook has managed to gather some insights into the importance of certain variable when attempting to predict a no-show, however the findings are certainly not conclusive. Over the course of this notebook, the analysis faced certain challenges and limitation:

Analysis Limitations¶

  • The data collected was from the month of May in 2016, although it presented over 100,000 entries, the dataset is not large enough, and data collected in another month may vary.
  • There is limited data for certain values, such as specific neighbourhoods, which hinders a proper analysis of no-show rates across neighbourhoods
  • There is a slight ambiguity regarding the handicap variable, and what the values represent.
  • There were unusual data present in the dataset, such as age being recorded as -1, and appointments made before the scheduling date.
  • The analysis done in this notebook was to compare the no-show counts and percentages between the values in each variable, which is by no means indicative of a variables significance in predicting no-shows
  • the variables were analysed individually, without considering how combination of variables may affect the no-show rate

From analysis done in this notebook, the variables: age, neighbourhood, hypertension, handicap, diabetes, handicap, SMS received, and number of days wait may be more useful to in predicting patient no-shows. Other variables such as gender, alcoholism and the day of the medical appointment do not seem to be as important when trying to predict no-shows in the medical appointments.

As mentioned earlier, the findings in this notebook are not definitive that the mentioned variable are more important in predicting no-show. More analysis needs to be conducted to better understand the relationship between variables and how that is reflected in the no-show. The analysis done in this notebook merely a glimpse into the relationship of the variables against patient no-shows, that hopefully inspires future research into the dataset.
